{{Distinguish|Jingu-kyo}}{{Short description|Japanese new religious movement which emerged from Shinto}} {{Expand Japanese|date=December 2018}} [[File:Sayo Kitamura.JPG|thumb|Sayo Kitamura]] [[File:Muga no Mai.JPG|thumb|Muga no Mai (Tensho Kotaijingu-Kyo's dance), 1948]] '''Tenshō Kōtai Jingūkyō''' ([[:en:Japanese language|Japanese]] {{lang|ja|天照皇大神宮教}}) is a Japanese [[:en:New religious movement|New religious movement]] which emerged from [[Shinto]]. It was established by [[:en:Sayo Kitamura|Sayo Kitamura]] ({{lang|ja|北村 サヨ}}) (1900–1967), with activities beginning in 1945. The movement includes 450,000 members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.kokugakuin.ac.jp/ijcc/wp/glossary/def_T.html|title=Glossary of Shinto Names and Terms: T|website=www2.kokugakuin.ac.jp|language=ja|access-date=2018-10-16}}</ref> Kitamura claimed possession by [[Amaterasu]] under the title Tenshō-Kōtaijin.
Its headquarters are in [[:en:Tabuse|Tabuse]] ({{lang|ja|田布施町}}, ''Tabuse-chō''), a town in the district of [[:en:Kumage District, Yamaguchi|Kumage District]], [[:en:Yamaguchi Prefecture|Yamaguchi]], [[:en:Japan|Japan]].
Followers practice a dance called ''muga no mai'' ({{lang|ja|無我の舞}}, "Dance of the non-self" or "Dance of the non-ego"), which is why the religion is called the "dancing religion" ({{lang|ja|踊る宗教}}, ''Odoru shūkyō'').
== See also == * [[:en:Anatta|Anatta]] / Anātman (jap. ''muga'')
